solutions.content:
When using dynamic programming, there is one condition: "Subproblem dependency should be acyclic".
In this problem, draw condition form a circle in graph. When DP enconter this case, there is no way to determine a draw. Fake draw will appear. 

Provid this game is a perfect information game. We can use the following features:
1. In a perfect information game, once the starting state is fixed, if everyone take optimal strategy, the result of the game will be deterministic. 
2. The final cat win or mouse win status is already defined. We can find all the other cat win and mouse win statuse base on it. The rest wil be draw.
3. DP can be used as long as subproblem dependency is acyclic.

Now let's get into the detail on this problem. The state can be determined by mouse position, cat position and whose turn to move. Once in a state, if cat and mouse take optimal strategy, the final result is deterministic(cat win/mouse win/draw). Based on the given graph, we can build a status graph (the status graph is directional).
For easy understanding, we will seperate cat win and mouse win. After we get all the cat win and mouse win status, the rest will be draw. We will asume all the player use optimal strategy.

Cat win case:
1. Final cat win cases are defined by the problem. Cat and mouse are at the same position. Cat cannot be at 0. 
2. If current state is cat win, and it's mouse's turn to move. The previous state will be cat's turn to move. If cat can move to this state (connected in the state graph) , he will move. 
3. If current state is cat win, and it's cat's turn to move. The previous state will be mouse's turn to move. Mouse will not choose to move to this state, if mouse have better choice. Base on this point, a state is mouse's turn to move, and all the possible choices lead to cat win. Then the state will be cat win. We can deal with this case(cat win, cat's turn) with the following method: if the edge pointing to this case, we can cut off the edge and look at the parent state (where the edge come from); if there is no other edge coming out from the parent edge (parent state do not have other choice), the parent state can be determined and it is cat win.

Mouse win case:
1. Final mouse win case is defined. Mouse is at position 0.
2. If current state is mouse win, and it's cat's turn to move. The previous state is mouse's turn to move. If mouse can move to this state (connected in the state graph) , he will move.
3. If current state is mouse win, and it's mouse's turn to move. The previous state will be cat's turn to move. Cat will not choose to move to this state, if cat have better choice. Base on this point, a state is cat's turn to move, and all the possible choices lead to mouse win. Then the state will be mouse win.

Further optimization: we only use small portion information of the state graph. The information needed can be reduced to 3 dimension array.
```
        public int CatMouseGame(int[][] graph)
        {
            //mouse win 1
            //cat win 2
            //draw 0
            //[mousePosition,catPosition, whoesturn],whoesturn:  0-> mouse;   1-> cat
            int len = graph.Length;

            int[,,] dp = new int[len, len, 2];
            int[,,] reducedStateGraph = new int[len, len, 2];

            //mouse move->simulate mouse move edge in state graph
            for (int mousePo = 0; mousePo < len; mousePo++)
            {
                for (int catPo = 1; catPo < len; catPo++)//cat is not allowed to reach 0
                {
                    reducedStateGraph[mousePo, catPo, 0] = graph[mousePo].Length;
                }
            }
            //cat move-> simulate cat move edge in state graph
            for (int catPo = 1; catPo < len; catPo++)
            {
                bool contains0 = graph[catPo].Contains(0);
                for (int mousePo = 0; mousePo < len; mousePo++)
                {
                    reducedStateGraph[mousePo, catPo, 1] = graph[catPo].Length;

                    //cat is not allowed to reach 0.
                    if (contains0)
                    {
                        reducedStateGraph[mousePo, catPo, 1]--;
                    }
                }
            }

            Queue<int[]> catWinQ = new Queue<int[]>();
            //init cat win
            for (int i = 1; i < len; i++)
            {
                dp[i, i, 0] = 2;
                dp[i, i, 1] = 2;
                catWinQ.Enqueue(new int[] { i, i, 0 });
                catWinQ.Enqueue(new int[] { i, i, 1 });
            }

            Queue<int[]> mouseWinQ = new Queue<int[]>();
            //init mouse win
            for (int i = 1; i < len; i++)
            {
                dp[0, i, 0] = 1; 
                dp[0, i, 1] = 1;
                mouseWinQ.Enqueue(new int[] { 0, i, 0 });
                mouseWinQ.Enqueue(new int[] { 0, i, 1 });
            }

            //bfs cat win ->2
            while (catWinQ.Count > 0)
            {
                int[] po = catWinQ.Dequeue();
                int currentMousePo = po[0];
                int currentCatPo = po[1];
                if (po[2] == 0) //mouse move
                {
                    //parent state is cat move, cat will choose to move to this po
                    foreach (int preCatPo in graph[currentCatPo])
                    {
                        if (preCatPo != 0 && dp[currentMousePo, preCatPo, 1] == 0)
                        {
                            dp[currentMousePo, preCatPo, 1] = 2;
                            catWinQ.Enqueue(new int[] { currentMousePo, preCatPo, 1 });
                        }
                    }
                }
                else  //cat move
                {
                    //parent state is mouse move, mouse will try to avoid move here
                    foreach (int preMousePo in graph[currentMousePo])
                    {
                        if (dp[preMousePo, currentCatPo, 0] == 0)
                        {
                            reducedStateGraph[preMousePo, currentCatPo, 0]--;
                            if (reducedStateGraph[preMousePo, currentCatPo, 0] == 0)
                            {
                                dp[preMousePo, currentCatPo, 0] = 2;
                                catWinQ.Enqueue(new int[] { preMousePo, currentCatPo, 0 });
                            }
                        }
                    }
                }
            }

            //bfs mouse win -> 1
            while (mouseWinQ.Count > 0)
            {
                int[] po = mouseWinQ.Dequeue();
                int currentMousePo = po[0];
                int currentCatPo = po[1];

                if (po[2] == 0)//mouse move
                {
                    //parent move is cat move, cat will try to avoid it
                    foreach (int preCatPo in graph[currentCatPo])
                    {
                        if (preCatPo != 0 && dp[currentMousePo, preCatPo, 1] == 0)
                        {
                            reducedStateGraph[currentMousePo, preCatPo, 1]--;
                            if (reducedStateGraph[currentMousePo, preCatPo, 1] == 0)
                            {
                                dp[currentMousePo, preCatPo, 1] = 1;
                                mouseWinQ.Enqueue(new int[] { currentMousePo, preCatPo, 1 });
                            }
                        }
                    }
                }
                else//cat move
                {
                    //parent move is mouse move, mouse will choose to move here
                    foreach (int preMousePo in graph[currentMousePo])
                    {
                        if (dp[preMousePo, currentCatPo, 0] == 0)
                        {
                            dp[preMousePo, currentCatPo, 0] = 1;
                            mouseWinQ.Enqueue(new int[] { preMousePo, currentCatPo, 0 });
                        }
                    }
                }

            }

            return dp[1, 2, 0];
        }
