solutions.content:
Working approach at 1500ms with 6.17% performance usind 4d DP.
1. We will try to solve this problem using recursion, later on we can add memoization to reduce complexity.
2. For each state, we have 4 dimensions i.e mouse for mouse location node, cat is the node at which cat is present, turn is either 0 or 1 if the it is mouse or cat's turn respectively and totalTurns represent the total numbers of turns taken till now. For 1 movement of mouse and then its cat, we have 1 complete turn.
3. If current turn is of mouse, then it will try to win or return 1, it that is not possible then it will atleast try to draw the game. But if draw is also not possible then it will let cat win.
4. If current turn is of cat, then it will try to win the game or return 2, if that is not possible, then it will try to draw the game if that is also not possible, then let mouse win.
5. Now, discuss end cases to end the recursion.
    5.1. If all the nodes of graph are visited by both mouse or cat, and still result is not found, then we can draw the game. I know it is not easy to get this test case but we have to add it otherwise it will fail for some cases. I have used 3*graph.length which is working fine. For values greater than 3, code is working but it is taking more time and for 2 it has failed for a test case.
    5.2. When mouse is at node 1, and cat is at node 2 and it is mouse turn just like beginning and totalTurns is greater than 0, then we can return 0 as everything is same as beginning.
    5.3. If mouse is at node 0 and it is cat's turn, then mouse is already won. So, return 1.
    5.4. If it is mouse turn and cat is already at mouse location. Cat has eaten the mouse and cat has won.
6. Finally, we can add memoization to make the code work for lengthy testcases.

Note - This problem is based on minimax principle and we can also refer a better problem (link - https://cp-algorithms.com/game_theory/games_on_graphs.html) it is very famouse problem.

As, we can notice, that is a graph problem and end condition is not much defined if we use DP or DFS. But what if we start from the winning, loosing and draw conditions using some other approach as discussed in LeetCode official solution. Please refer that solution as it is much faster and better but not intuitive untill we have solved some problems like that.

``` java
class Solution {
    private Integer[][][][] dp;
    public int catMouseGame(int[][] graph) {
        int n = graph.length;
        dp = new Integer[n+1][n+1][2][3*n+1];
        return catMouseBothMove(graph, 1, 2, 0, 0);        
    }
    /*
    @turn : 0 - mouse, 1 - cat
    */
    private int catMouseBothMove(int[][] graph, int mouse, int cat, int turn, int totalTurns){
        // End Case - 1
        if(totalTurns == graph.length*3) return 0;
        // Check for draw, End case - 2
        if(mouse == 1 && cat == 2 && turn == 0 && totalTurns > 0) return 0;

        // Check if mouse wins or not, End case - 3
        if(mouse == 0 && turn == 1) return 1;

        // Check if cat wins or not, End case - 4
        if(turn == 0 && cat == mouse) return 2;
        if(dp[mouse][cat][turn][totalTurns] != null) return dp[mouse][cat][turn][totalTurns];
        int result;
        // If current turn is of mouse
        if(turn == 0){
            result = 2;
            for(int v : graph[mouse]){
                if(v != cat){
                    int res = catMouseBothMove(graph, v, cat, 1, totalTurns);
                    if(res == 1){
                        result = 1;
                        break;
                    }
                    if(res == 0){
                        result = 0;
                    } 
                }
            }
        }
        // cat's turn or turn is equal to 1
        else{
            result = 1;
            for(int v : graph[cat]){
                if(v != 0){
                    int res = catMouseBothMove(graph, mouse, v, 0, totalTurns+1);
                    if(res == 2){
                        result = 2;
                        break;
                    }
                    if(res == 0){
                        result = 0;
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        return dp[mouse][cat][turn][totalTurns] = result;
    }
}

