solutions.content:
The key to pass the last test case is to **check whether the current state can win at first** and then move to the next state. 
Since we set the state to **DRAW**  at first and then move to next state, you can see the case that [@nguyen_hoanh](https://leetcode.com/nguyen_hoanh) said in  [here](https://leetcode.com/problems/cat-and-mouse/discuss/176029/Why-this-solution-did-not-work/) will fail.
Here is the **incorrect** code that check the cat turn's state inside the next for loop:
```java
// cat turn
result = 1;
for (int i = 0; i < graph[cat].length; i++) {
    // cat can't travel to the hole
    if (graph[cat][i] == 0) {
        continue;
    }
    // NOTE: check inside will fail!
    if (graph[cat][i] == mouse) {
        dp[mouse][cat][who] = 2;
        return 2;
    }
    int res = dfs(graph, dp, mouse, graph[cat][i], who ^ 1);
    // cat win
    if (res == 2) {
        dp[mouse][cat][who] = 2;
        return 2;
    // draw
    } else if (res == 0) {
        result = 0;
    }
}
```
Here is the AC code:
```java
class Solution {
    public int catMouseGame(int[][] graph) {
        int[][][] dp = new int[graph.length][graph.length][2];
        for (int i = 0; i < graph.length; i++) {           
            for (int j = 0; j < graph.length; j++) {
                Arrays.fill(dp[i][j], -1);             
            }          
        }
        int ans = dfs(graph, dp, 1, 2, 0);
        return ans;
    }

    public int dfs(int[][] graph, int[][][] dp, int mouse, int cat, int who) {
        if (dp[mouse][cat][who] != -1) {
            return dp[mouse][cat][who];
        }
        // set the status to draw
        dp[mouse][cat][who] = 0;        
        int result;
        // mouse turn				
        if (who == 0) {
            // check if mouse can win
            // NOTE: this must be done before the next for loop rather than during it.
            for (int i = 0; i < graph[mouse].length; i++) {
                if (graph[mouse][i] == 0) {
                    dp[mouse][cat][who] = 1;
                    return 1;
                }
            }
            // next move
            result = 2;
            for (int i = 0; i < graph[mouse].length; i++) {  
                if (graph[mouse][i] != cat) {
                    int res = dfs(graph, dp, graph[mouse][i], cat, who ^ 1);
                    // cat win
                    if (res == 1) {
                        dp[mouse][cat][who] = 1;
                        return 1;
                    // draw
                    } else if (res == 0) {
                        result = 0;
                    }
                }
            }
        // cat turn
        } else {
            // check if cat can win
            // NOTE: this must be done before the next for loop rather than during it.						
            for (int i = 0; i < graph[cat].length; i++) {
                if (graph[cat][i] == mouse) {
                    dp[mouse][cat][who] = 2;
                    return 2;
                }
            }
            // next move
            result = 1;
            for (int i = 0; i < graph[cat].length; i++) {
                // cat can't travel to the hole
                if (graph[cat][i] == 0) {
                    continue;
                }                
                int res = dfs(graph, dp, mouse, graph[cat][i], who ^ 1);
                // cat win
                if (res == 2) {
                    dp[mouse][cat][who] = 2;
                    return 2;
                // draw
                } else if (res == 0) {
                    result = 0;
                }
            }
        }
        dp[mouse][cat][who] = result;
        return dp[mouse][cat][who];
    }
}
