solutions.content:
Since there exists only (2 * n) * n * n states in this game, we can use memorized recursion.

[Reference](https://leetcode.com/problems/cat-and-mouse/discuss/298937/DP-memory-status-search-search-strait-forward-and-easy-to-understand)

I defined the vector as follows:
`memo[iteration][the position of mouse][the position of cat] := 0 (if draw) or 1 (if mouse will win) or 2 (if cat will win)` 
In other words, we can know which player will win by referring to this vector when we have the situation where the mouse is at `x` and the cat is at `y` at the `t` (0 round is the initial state) round.

Now, I will move to the detail of the algorithm.
1. I will set all the values of vector to `-1 `, which implies unknown region.
2. Then, we will set `(x, y, t) = (1, 2, 0)` and start recursion.
3. Each iteration, both player will try to find out which player can win when it takes each possible node.
4. If the currenct player could find the next action leading to winning, it will just take this action immediately.
5. If it could not find any ways to win, then it will try to take the way to not lose. If there is no way to avoid losing, then this state will record as losing.
6. In the end, both players can know which player will win when they try to take the way to win or the way to not lose.

If you stop using `pair<int, int>`, then you can speed up the code.

**NOTE**: I checked the test case [here](https://leetcode.com/problems/cat-and-mouse/discuss/176177/Most-of-the-DFS-solutions-are-WRONG-check-this-case) as well.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int catMouseGame(vector<vector<int>>& graph){
        int n = graph.size();
        vector<pair<int, int>> player = {{1, 2}, {2, 1}}; // {{mouse, cat}, {cat, mouse}}
        vector<vector<vector<int>>> memo(2 * n, vector<vector<int>>(n, vector<int>(n, -1)));

        auto rec = [&](auto rec, int itr, int mouse, int cat)->int{
            if (itr == 2 * n) return 0; // termination criterion (no where to go next)
            int& result = memo[itr][mouse][cat]; int cur_player, nxt_player; bool lose = true;
            if (!mouse) return result = 1; // the mouse is at the hole
            if (cat == mouse) return result = 2; // the cat catches the mouse
            if (result != -1) return result; // if we already know the answer of this state, return the value

            tie(cur_player, nxt_player) = player[itr % 2];
            auto update = [&](int mouse_nxt, int cat_nxt)->bool{
                if (!cat_nxt) return false; // the cat cannot go into the hole.
                int winner = rec(rec, itr + 1, mouse_nxt, cat_nxt); // the winner of this state.
                if (winner == cur_player) result = cur_player; // This state leads to winning.
                else if (winner != nxt_player) lose = false; // In the worst case, the current player can take this strategy to avoid losing.
                return winner == cur_player; // If result is updated, return true, otherwise false.
            };

            if (itr % 2) for (auto& nxt: graph[cat]) {if (update(mouse, nxt)) return cur_player;}
            else for (auto& nxt: graph[mouse]) {if (update(nxt, cat)) return cur_player;}
            return result = (lose ? nxt_player : 0); // if there is no way to win, the current player will take the strategy not to lose.
        };
        return rec(rec, 0, 1, 2);
    }
};
```

