solutions.content:
This is inspired by https://leetcode.com/problems/cat-and-mouse/discuss/298937/DP-memory-status-search-search-strait-forward-and-easy-to-understand, except I don't try 2N steps, stop where no furether progress is possible.

Further optimization possible.

1. Finit States
So, the game can only be in a finite number of states, identified by 3 variables:

(mouse /*mouse position*/, cat /*cat position*/, mouseMove /*if mouse should make the next move*/)

For example, the initial state is:
(1, 2, True)

Each state can transition to a number of other states:

For example:
(1, 2, True) -> (3, 2, False) ...

Cause the space of this problem is finite, only finite number of states should be calculated.


2. Unknown and known states

For a few states, we easyly know if cat wins or mouse wins, for example:

(0, 3, False) -> mouse wins
(1, 1, True) -> cat wins

Most states are uknown at the begining. But using the known states as seeds, we can know more states step by step, until we reach the initial stae (1, 2, True). If (1, 2, True) is known, we have the answer. It is possible that no clean path to (1, 2, True), that means, there is a loop dependency in unknown states. In that case, the game end in a draw.

3. Topology sorting (just an idea, I didn't implement this part)
It should be totally possible to build a dependency graph, and solve those states who don't depend on uknowns, therefore further optimize this algorithm. However this is already complicate enough, during an interview let's go no further unless asked to.



```
public class Solution {
    private Dictionary<Tuple<int, int, bool>, int> map = new Dictionary<Tuple<int, int, bool>, int> ();
    private int[][] graph;

    // Try a unknown state,best effort
    private int TryMove(Tuple<int, int, bool> state) {

        (var mouse, var cat, var mouseMove) = state;

        if (mouse == 0)
            map[state]= 1;

        if (cat == mouse)
            map[state] =2;


        if(map.ContainsKey(state)) {
            if (map[state] >= 0){
                return map[state];
            }
            else {
                // If this state has been tried before, still not solved, then don't attempt to solve it now to avoid infinite loop
                return -1;
            }
        }
        else {
            // If a new state is introduced, mark it as unknown. We'll attempt to solve it in this call, but if we cannot,
            // feel free to leave it to the next loop
            map[state] = -1;
        }

        if (mouseMove) {
            var results = graph[mouse].Select( n => TryMove(new Tuple<int, int, bool>(n, cat, false))).Distinct();
            if (results.Contains(1)) {
                map[state] = 1;
            }
            else if (results.Contains(-1)) {
                map[state] = -1;
            }
            else {
                map[state] = 2;
            }
        }
        else {
            var results = graph[cat].Where( n => n != 0).Select( n => TryMove(new Tuple<int, int, bool>(mouse, n, true))).Distinct();
            if (results.Contains(2)) {
                map[state] = 2;
            }
            else if (results.Contains(-1)) {
                map[state] = -1;
            }
            else {
                map[state] = 1;
            }
        }

        return map[state];
    }

    public int CatMouseGame(int[][] graph) {
        this.graph = graph;

        var keyCount = 0;
        var unknownCount = 0;
        map[new Tuple<int, int, bool>(1,2,true)] = -1; // Initial state


        do{
            keyCount = map.Keys.Count();
            unknownCount = map.Values.Where(x => x == -1).Count();

            var todo = map.Where( x => x.Value == -1).ToList();
            // Just try to reoslve all unsolved states - it is possible to use topology sorting to find out which 
            // unsolved state only depend on known states, only try those, therefore further optimize this
            // algorithm
            foreach (var kvp in todo){
                map.Remove(kvp.Key);
                TryMove(kvp.Key);
            }

            if (map[new Tuple<int, int, bool>(1,2,true)] >= 0)
                return map[new Tuple<int, int, bool>(1,2,true)];
		 // Keep trying as long as we're making progress
		 // If we introduce new keys, or solve any unknown state, that means we're making progress
        } while (keyCount != map.Keys.Count() || unknownCount != map.Values.Where(x => x == -1).Count());


        return 0;
    }
}
