To solve this problem, first of all we check if the length of the string is equal to **1**, if it is, we return an empty string **(" ")**.
For convenience, we turn the string into an **array**.
Now we do a search on the first half of the array (we add '**~~**' to remove the fractional part if the number is not paired), since this is a polyndrom, it makes no sense for us to sort through the second part.
In case we find a character that is **greater** than '**a**', we change it to '**a**'. But if the whole string consists **only** of characters equal to '**a**', we take the **last** **one** and change it to '**b**'.
At the end, it remains only to collect the string from the array again.

```
let breakPalindrome = function (palindrome) {
    if (palindrome.length === 1) return '';
    let arr = Array.from(palindrome);

    for (let i = 0; i < ~~(arr.length / 2 ); i++) {
        if (arr[i] > 'a') {
            arr[i] = 'a';
            return arr.join('');
        }
    }
    arr[arr.length - 1] = 'b';
    return arr.join('');
};
```

