# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Since your answer should be a lexicograpical string and it should not be a palindrome then you must have to play with only 'a' and 'b'.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
My method was fairly straightforward: iterate through the string and, whenever you come across a character other than 'a', just replace it with 'a'.

 There are a few edge cases.
For example, if every character in the string is 'a', you must simply change the last character to 'b'. Another edge case is that if the string is an odd length, you must skip the middle character because doing so would cause the string to become a palindrome after the change.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n) 
The worst case scenario, when every character is 'a', 
it requires you to iterate through the entire string.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(1)
NO Extra Space required.
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    string breakPalindrome(string palindrome) {

        if(palindrome.size() == 1)
            return "";

        for(int i = 0; i < palindrome.size()-1; i++){
            if(i == palindrome.size()/2 && palindrome.size() & 1){
                continue;
            }
            if(palindrome[i] != 'a'){
                palindrome[i] = 'a';
                return palindrome;
            }
        }
        palindrome[palindrome.size()-1] = 'b';

        return palindrome;
    }
};
```

