solutions.content:
To understand the problem, let's summarise what we're expected to do:
1. We **must** substitute exactly one character
2. The result **must not** be a palindrome
3. If there are multiple strings that satisfy #1 and #2, we pick the lexicographically smallest one

A palindrome is a string with central symmetry, meaning that for any `std::string s` which is a palindrome, and `auto l = s.length()` the following is true:
```
s[i] == s[l-i-1] for i in range [0, l-1]
```
This leads to **the first insight**: *any* character we replace will break the palindrome condition, with the exception of the centre position for strings with odd number of characters:
```
std::string s1 = "abba";   // replacing any character makes s1 a non-palindrome
std::string s2 = "abcba"; // here, replacing 'c' with anything doesn't change a thing, since 'c' is at the centre position
```
We can take this insight further and use the fact that the input string is a palindrome to only scan its left half, since the right half must be its reflection.

**The second insight** is: replacing the leftmost non `'a'` character with `'a'` produces a lexicographically smallest string:
```
std::string s = "bbbbb"; // out of all ways to modify s, "abbbb" is the lexicographically smallest one
```

Finally, **the third insight** is: if all characters (regardless of the one at the centre) are `'a'`, then replacing the rightmost one with `'b'` creates the lexicographically smallest modification:
```
std::string s = "aaaaa"; // out of all variations, "aaaab" is the lexicographically smallest
```

Now we simply need to combine all three insights together:

```
class Solution {
public:
    string breakPalindrome(string palindrome) {
        if (palindrome.length() < 2) return std::string();

        int indexLimit = palindrome.length() >> 1;
        auto i{0};

        for (; i != indexLimit; ++i) {
            if (palindrome[i] > 'a') {
                palindrome[i] = 'a';                
                break;
            }
        }

        if (i == indexLimit) {
            palindrome.back() = 'b';
        }

        return std::move(palindrome); // this will allow re-using memory inside palindrome instead of copying it
    }
};
```

Runtime complexity is **O(n)** where `n` is `palindrome.length()`, because we sequentially scan a half of the input string. Space complexity is **O(1)** since we only need two extra integers to run the algorithm.
Overall, it runs comfortably at 0 ms:

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/715c3c20-be25-400a-926f-0f6976ed465f_1665422898.9552605.png)

If you have any questions, don't hesitate to ask =)
**Also, please consider upvoting this post if you found it useful**

